You're very close! Array and list indices in Java (and many other languages) are zero-based, meaning the first element is at index 0, and the last element is at `size - 1`. Your code tries to access `size`, which is one index too high. Here's the fix:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> fruits = new ArrayList<>();
        fruits.add("Apple");
        fruits.add("Banana");
        fruits.add("Cherry");

        String lastFruit = fruits.get(fruits.size() - 1); // Corrected index
        System.out.println("Last fruit: " + lastFruit);
    }
}
```
Always remember to subtract one when using `size()` or `length` to get the last index. Happy coding!

This is a common little mix-up! In C#, a single equals sign (`=`) is for *assignment*, not comparison. So, `status = "active"` is actually assigning 'active' to `status`, and then the `if` statement evaluates the result of that assignment (which is `true` for non-null strings). To compare, you need two equals signs (`==`):

```csharp
string status = "inactive";

if (status == "active") // Changed = to == for comparison
{
    Console.WriteLine("Status is active!");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Status is not active.");
}
```
With that small change, your `if` statement will work exactly as intended! Anything else I can clarify?

