Certainly! Your Java code checks if `value` is not `null` before attempting to call `toString()` on it, preventing a `NullPointerException`. This is a common defensive programming practice.

A more modern Java approach, especially for optional values, uses `Optional`:

```java
import java.util.Optional;

// Assuming 'value' could be null
String value = "Hello"; // Or null

Optional.ofNullable(value).ifPresent(v -> System.out.println(v.toString()));
// Or simply: Optional.ofNullable(value).ifPresent(System.out::println);
```
`Optional` makes the intent clearer that a value might be absent. Does this fit your use case well?

Absolutely! Your PHP code checks if `$variable` is not set, and if so, assigns it a default string. This ensures `$variable` always has a value before being used.

PHP 7 introduced the null coalescing operator (`??`) which is perfect for this:

```php
// Imagine $_GET['param'] might not be set
$paramValue = $_GET['param'] ?? 'default_value';

echo $paramValue;
```
This single line achieves the same result much more concisely. It's quite handy for handling optional input! Would you like to see it used with other examples?

