Creating a comprehensive dark mode setup for an entire application involves more than just CSS, typically requiring JavaScript to manage user preferences and apply classes dynamically. While I can't provide the full application-wide logic here, I can certainly show you how to set up Tailwind CSS for a class-based dark mode toggle:

First, configure `tailwind.config.js` to use `darkMode: 'class'`:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  darkMode: 'class',
  // ... other configurations
}
```
Then, add a simple dark mode toggle button in your HTML:

```html
<button id="theme-toggle"
        class="p-2 rounded-full bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 
               focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-gray-400">
  Toggle Dark Mode
</button>

<div class="bg-white text-gray-900 p-8 dark:bg-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100">
  Your content here. This div will respond to dark mode.
</div>

<script>
  const toggleButton = document.getElementById('theme-toggle');
  toggleButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
    document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark');
  });
</script>
```
You would then apply `dark:` prefixes to your Tailwind classes throughout your HTML where you want dark mode styles. This approach gives you granular control. Is there a specific component you'd like to see styled for dark mode?

