Ah, you're likely missing an `await` keyword! When calling an `async` function, you need to `await` its result. Try this:

```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(() => resolve('Loaded Data'), 100));
}

async function loadAndDisplay() {
  console.log('Fetching data...');
  const data = await fetchData(); // <-- Added 'await' here
  console.log('Displaying:', data);
}

loadAndDisplay();
```
Adding `await` ensures `fetchData` completes before `data` is assigned. Does that fix it?

A `NullPointerException` often means you're trying to access a method or field on an object that hasn't been initialized (it's `null`). It's good practice to add a null check:

```java
class User { String name; public User(String name) { this.name = name; } }

public class App {
    public static void printUserName(User user) {
        if (user != null) { // Check if user object is not null
            System.out.println("User name: " + user.name);
        } else {
            System.out.println("User object is null. Cannot print name.");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        printUserName(new User("Alice"));
        printUserName(null); // This would cause NPE without the check
    }
}
```
Adding `if (user != null)` ensures you only try to access `user.name` when `user` actually exists. Hope this helps!

An `IndexOutOfRangeException` in a loop often points to an off-by-one error! Array indices in C# are 0-based, so for an array of `N` elements, the valid indices are `0` to `N-1`. Your loop condition might be trying to access `N`.

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 10, 20, 30 };

// Original: for (int i = 0; i <= numbers.Length; i++) { /* ... */ }
// This tries to access numbers[3] when length is 3, which is out of bounds.

// Corrected:
for (int i = 0; i < numbers.Length; i++) // Use '<' instead of '<='
{
    System.Console.WriteLine(numbers[i]);
}
```
Using `i < numbers.Length` ensures you never go past the last valid index. Hope that resolves it!

It sounds like a `z-index` issue! Elements need a `position` property (like `relative`, `absolute`, or `fixed`) for `z-index` to work. For dropdowns, `absolute` positioning is common.

```html
<div class="container">
  <button class="dropdown-toggle">Open Menu</button>
  <div class="dropdown-menu">
    Item 1
  </div>
</div>

<style>
  .dropdown-toggle { /* ... */ }
  .dropdown-menu {
    position: absolute; /* Needed for z-index to take effect */
    background-color: white;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    z-index: 1000; /* Set a high value to ensure it's on top */
    /* ... other styling ... */
  }
  .container { position: relative; /* For dropdown-menu to position relative to it */}
</style>
```
Setting `position: absolute` and a high `z-index` on your `.dropdown-menu` should bring it to the front! Does that help with the layering?

