Great question! Your `addContent` function uses `document.write` to add an `<h1>` tag to the document. While it works for very simple, synchronous content injection during page load, `document.write` has some significant drawbacks.

Primarily, if `document.write` is called *after* the page has fully loaded (e.g., in a `setTimeout` or an event handler), it will overwrite the *entire* current document, effectively erasing your page. It also has performance implications and can block rendering.

Instead of trying to 'clean up' `document.write` itself, the modern and much safer approach is to manipulate the DOM (Document Object Model) directly using methods like `appendChild`, `innerHTML`, or `insertAdjacentHTML`. Here's a cleaner way to add an `<h1>` without overwriting your page:

```javascript
function addContentModern(message) {
  const newHeading = document.createElement('h1'); // Create an H1 element
  newHeading.textContent = message; // Set its text content

  // Append it to an existing element, e.g., the body or a specific div
  document.body.appendChild(newHeading);

  // Alternative using innerHTML for simpler cases (less safe for user-generated content)
  // document.body.innerHTML += `<h1>${message}</h1>`; 
}

// Usage after the page has loaded:
addContentModern("Welcome to our modern page!");
```
This method safely adds content without side effects. It's the recommended practice for dynamic content updates in web pages. Would you like to see how to add content to a specific `div`?

