You've got it! Your current Java code creates a *new* `String` object in memory with each `+=` operation inside the loop, which can be inefficient for many iterations due to repeated object creation and garbage collection.

For better performance when building strings in a loop, it's best to use `StringBuilder`:

```java
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Arrays;

public class StringConcatenation {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> words = Arrays.asList("Hello", "world", "Java");
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (String s : words) {
            sb.append(s).append(" ");
        }
        String result = sb.toString().trim(); // Use trim() to remove trailing space
        System.out.println(result); // Outputs: Hello world Java
    }
}
```
`StringBuilder` modifies an internal buffer directly, making it much more efficient. Happy to help with more Java!

Absolutely! Your C# snippet uses a ternary operator (`condition ? value_if_true : value_if_false`) to check if `GetUserName()` returns a non-null value. If it does, `name` is used; otherwise, "Guest" is assigned.

C# offers the null-coalescing operator (`??`) for a much cleaner approach:

```csharp
using System;

public class NullCoalescingExample
{
    static string GetUserName() => null; // Example method that might return null

    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string name = GetUserName();
        string displayName = name ?? "Guest";

        Console.WriteLine($"Welcome, {displayName}!"); // Outputs: Welcome, Guest!
    }
}
```
This `??` operator provides a default value if the left-hand operand is null. It's quite handy, isn't it?

Of course! Your PHP code checks if a `page` parameter exists in the `$_GET` superglobal using `isset()`. If it does, `$page` is set to that value; otherwise, it defaults to `1`.

PHP 7+ introduced the null coalescing operator (`??`), which makes this much cleaner:

```php
<?php
// Simulate $_GET['page'] not being set initially
// unset($_GET['page']); 

// Simulate $_GET['page'] being set for demonstration
// $_GET['page'] = 5;

$page = $_GET['page'] ?? 1;

echo "Current page: " . $page; // Outputs: Current page: 1 (if not set) or Current page: 5 (if set)
?>
```
This operator checks if the left operand is set and not null; if so, it uses that value; otherwise, it uses the right operand. Very neat!

